TY  - JOUR
T1  - Evidence on Bidding Strategies and the Information in Treasury Bill Auctions
AU  - Cammack, Elizabeth B.
Y1  - 1991/02/01
PY  - 1991
DA  - 1991/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261742
DO  - 10.1086/261742
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 100
EP  - 130
VL  - 99
IS  - 1
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - The empirical results presented suggest that imperfect information is present in the Treasury bill market. The mean auction price for 3-month bills is, on average, four basis points below the comparable secondary market price for the 1973-84 period. This "downward biasing" is positively related to the anticipated amount of dispersion of auction bids. This suggests that auction bidders use a bidding strategy that accounts for their lack of agreement about the value of the bill. Further, the secondary bill market learns from the bill auction, implying that these two markets aggregate traders' private information differently.
AB  - The empirical results presented suggest that imperfect information is present in the Treasury bill market. The mean auction price for 3-month bills is, on average, four basis points below the comparable secondary market price for the 1973-84 period. This "downward biasing" is positively related to the anticipated amount of dispersion of auction bids. This suggests that auction bidders use a bidding strategy that accounts for their lack of agreement about the value of the bill. Further, the secondary bill market learns from the bill auction, implying that these two markets aggregate traders' private information differently.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261742
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261742
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Rational Speculation
AU  - Leach, John
Y1  - 1991/02/01
PY  - 1991
DA  - 1991/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261743
DO  - 10.1086/261743
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 131
EP  - 144
VL  - 99
IS  - 1
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - The stationary equilibrium of an overlapping generations economy in which agents trade a single asset is examined. If agents live for only two periods, the selling prices follow an identically and independently distributed process. If agents live for more than two periods, the selling prices follow a Markov process. An implication of the model is that price bubbles can occur in a stationary, rational expectations equilibrium.
AB  - The stationary equilibrium of an overlapping generations economy in which agents trade a single asset is examined. If agents live for only two periods, the selling prices follow an identically and independently distributed process. If agents live for more than two periods, the selling prices follow a Markov process. An implication of the model is that price bubbles can occur in a stationary, rational expectations equilibrium.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261743
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261743
Y2  - 2024/03/22
